body: The model doesn't support batch inference.  Please try another model.  You may pick one from:https://github.com/mlperf/inference/tree/master/v0.5/classification_and_detection

Hi @abduld ,

Expanding on the answer, if you open-up the model using Netron (or any other tool) and examine the graph inputs, usually a model that natively supports "batching" has symbolic dimensions in the graph input shape descriptions. For example, like this - 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9969784/65905177-eccbc700-e374-11e9-91fe-f643c88a3a7b.png)

A model that doesn't usually has the input shape fixed like [1, 224, 224, 3].

Closing this issue as this is not an issue for ORT. 

Pleas re-open for further clarifications.

issue.title: Batch processing support for Inference

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
Hey Folks; I've been using onnxruntime (python API) for a little while and I'm planning to make a comparison in runtime performance with a few benchmarking frameworks such as pytorch, and tensorRT. And so far I've been successful in making 1 - off inference programs for all, including onnxruntime (which has been one of the easiest!)

I'm struggling now however, to figure out how to get onnx to process a stream of inputs (for simplicity, a fixed batch) in a performant way. Right now it seems like I need to load the onnx context for each input, which has some significant performance issues when the batch size >> 1. 
Do you happen to have any suggestions or potential code examples ( python/C# APIs would be ideal) that could help me give onnxruntime a more fair chance against some of the competing frameworks?
